<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="206" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,327,1289]" pageId="13" pageNumber="206">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,327,352]" pageId="13" pageNumber="206">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Recognized by its tiny size; reddish brown to fuscous, oval body (
<figureCitation box="[1071,1154,327,352]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1482,1504]" captionTargetBox="[205,1400,335,1427]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,303,1459]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 3. Holotype specimens of five new Thai phyline species in left lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253584/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="206">Figs. 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1170,1185,328,352]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1782,1804]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,303,1760]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,303,1760]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 4. Habitus images of living adult individuals of Thai phylines. A. Sejanus adustopaca, holotype male (Nakhon Nayok). B. D. anthophila, male (Nakhon Nayok). C. Ditto, female. D. D. taksini (Nakhon Nayok). E. Decomia indochinensis, male (Nakhon Nayok). F. Malaysiamiris nigrescens, male (SERS). G. Ditto, female. H. Tytthus chinensis, female (Nakhon Nayok). I. Lasiolabops cosmopolites, female (SERS). J. Sthenaridea rufescens, female (Chaiyaphum)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253585/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="206">4</figureCitation>
A); brownish, opaque hemelytron, without white macula at cuneal base; and form of male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[1054,1125,364,389]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1757,1779]" captionTargetBox="[173,1399,258,1696]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[151,1436,193,1735]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 9. Male genitalia of three new phyline species from Thailand." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253590/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="206">
Fig. 
<number box="[1109,1125,364,388]" pageId="13" pageNumber="206" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
). This new species is most similar in several facies (e.g., brownish coloration, shape of parameres) to the Australian 
<taxonomicName authority="Carvalho &amp; Gross, 1982" authorityName="Carvalho &amp; Gross" authorityYear="1982" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Sejanus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brittoni">
<emphasis box="[1179,1293,399,424]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="206">S. brittoni</emphasis>
Carvalho &amp; Gross, 
<number box="[235,294,436,460]" pageId="13" pageNumber="206" value="1982.0">1982</number>
</taxonomicName>
, from which 
<taxonomicName box="[456,618,436,461]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Sejanus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adustopaca">
<emphasis box="[456,618,436,461]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="206">S. adustopaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is readily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName box="[977,1094,436,461]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Sejanus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brittoni">
<emphasis box="[977,1094,436,461]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="206">S. brittoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the ovoid and tiny body, uniformly brownish dorsum, unicolorously brown antenna, and not apically broadened endosoma; in 
<taxonomicName box="[1315,1429,471,496]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Sejanus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brittoni">
<emphasis box="[1315,1429,471,496]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="206">S. brittoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the body is more elongate in male, the antennal segment II is bicolorous, and the apical part of the endosoma is broadened (for detailed information on characters of 
<taxonomicName box="[744,856,543,568]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Sejanus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brittoni">
<emphasis box="[744,856,543,568]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="206">S. brittoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, see Menard &amp; Schuh, 
<number box="[1120,1179,544,568]" pageId="13" pageNumber="206" value="2011.0">2011</number>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="206" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,327,1289]" pageId="13" pageNumber="206">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,580,605]" pageId="13" pageNumber="206">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[355,422,580,605]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="206">Male:</emphasis>
Body reddish brown to fuscous, ovoid; dorsal surface weakly shining, with uniformly distributed, pale, simple, reclining setae. Head brown, with rather wide vertex. Antenna unicolorously brown. Labium yellow brown, shining, little exceeding apex of mesocoxa; segment IV reddish. Pronotum short, reddish brown; scutellum dark brown, weakly arched; pleura uniformly brown. Hemelytron opaque, dark brown, somewhat roughened; anterior parts of corium and embolium tinged with red; membrane smoky brown. All coxae and legs shiny pale or yellowish brown, immaculate; metafemur with reddish apical half, tumid, 
<number box="[1244,1279,759,784]" pageId="13" pageNumber="206" value="2.5">2.5</number>
times as long as broad; claw with a narrowly developed pulvillus. Genitalia as in 
<figureCitation box="[931,1000,796,821]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1757,1779]" captionTargetBox="[173,1399,258,1696]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[151,1436,193,1735]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 9. Male genitalia of three new phyline species from Thailand." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/253590/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="206">
Fig. 
<number box="[984,1000,796,820]" pageId="13" pageNumber="206" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
; endosoma C-shaped, small, minutely rugulose apically. 
<emphasis box="[355,448,831,856]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="206">Female:</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
